Shared Qs (030)


  1. Question

    Let \(x(t)\) represent a train’s position as a function of time. For some train during some period of time, the position can be modeled with a quadratic function.

    \[x(t) = 6t^2+5t-10\]

    The velocity \(v(t)\) is also a function of time. The velocity function is the derivative (with respect to time) of the position function. The derivative can be defined using a limit.

    \[v(t) ~=~ \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{x(t+h)-x(t)}{h}\]

    Using this definition (and simplifying), you will find that \(v(t)\) is a linear function in time, which depends on the acceleration \(a\) and the initial velocity \(v_0\).

    \[v(t) ~=~ at+v_0\]

    Determine \(a\) and \(v_0\).

    • \(a=\)
    • \(v_0=\)


    Solution

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(6(t+h)^2+5(t+h)-10\right)-\left(6t^2+5t-10\right)}{h}\]

    We cannot simply replace \(h\) with \(0\), because we cannot divide by \(0\). Instead we will simplify.

    Distribute away the outer parentheses.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{6(t+h)^2+5(t+h)-10-6t^2-5t+10}{h}\]

    Expand the squared sum. (Remember FOIL.)

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{6(t^2+2th+h^2)+5(t+h)-10-6t^2-5t+10}{h}\]

    Distribute.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{6t^2+12th+6h^2+5t+5h-10-6t^2-5t+10}{h}\]

    Combine like terms in numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{12th+6h^2+5h}{h}\]

    All the terms in the numerator have a shared factor (\(h\)). Factor out \(h\) from the numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{(12t+6h+5)\cdot h}{h}\]

    Eliminate common factor from numerator and denominator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\left(12t+6h+5\right)\]

    Now, since there is no possibility of dividing by \(0\), we can substitute \(0\) for \(h\).

    \[v(t)~=~12t+6\cdot 0+5\]

    Simplify.

    \[v(t)~=~12t+5\]

    So, \(a=12\) and \(v_0=5\).



  2. Question

    Let \(x(t)\) represent a train’s position as a function of time. For some train during some period of time, the position can be modeled with a quadratic function.

    \[x(t) = 4t^2-8t+5\]

    The velocity \(v(t)\) is also a function of time. The velocity function is the derivative (with respect to time) of the position function. The derivative can be defined using a limit.

    \[v(t) ~=~ \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{x(t+h)-x(t)}{h}\]

    Using this definition (and simplifying), you will find that \(v(t)\) is a linear function in time, which depends on the acceleration \(a\) and the initial velocity \(v_0\).

    \[v(t) ~=~ at+v_0\]

    Determine \(a\) and \(v_0\).

    • \(a=\)
    • \(v_0=\)


    Solution

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(4(t+h)^2-8(t+h)+5\right)-\left(4t^2-8t+5\right)}{h}\]

    We cannot simply replace \(h\) with \(0\), because we cannot divide by \(0\). Instead we will simplify.

    Distribute away the outer parentheses.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{4(t+h)^2-8(t+h)+5-4t^2+8t-5}{h}\]

    Expand the squared sum. (Remember FOIL.)

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{4(t^2+2th+h^2)-8(t+h)+5-4t^2+8t-5}{h}\]

    Distribute.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{4t^2+8th+4h^2-8t-8h+5-4t^2+8t-5}{h}\]

    Combine like terms in numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{8th+4h^2-8h}{h}\]

    All the terms in the numerator have a shared factor (\(h\)). Factor out \(h\) from the numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{(8t+4h-8)\cdot h}{h}\]

    Eliminate common factor from numerator and denominator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\left(8t+4h-8\right)\]

    Now, since there is no possibility of dividing by \(0\), we can substitute \(0\) for \(h\).

    \[v(t)~=~8t+4\cdot 0-8\]

    Simplify.

    \[v(t)~=~8t-8\]

    So, \(a=8\) and \(v_0=-8\).

  4. Question

    Let \(x(t)\) represent a train’s position as a function of time. For some train during some period of time, the position can be modeled with a quadratic function.

    \[x(t) = -10t^2-9t-4\]

    The velocity \(v(t)\) is also a function of time. The velocity function is the derivative (with respect to time) of the position function. The derivative can be defined using a limit.

    \[v(t) ~=~ \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{x(t+h)-x(t)}{h}\]

    Using this definition (and simplifying), you will find that \(v(t)\) is a linear function in time, which depends on the acceleration \(a\) and the initial velocity \(v_0\).

    \[v(t) ~=~ at+v_0\]

    Determine \(a\) and \(v_0\).

    • \(a=\)
    • \(v_0=\)


    Solution

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(-10(t+h)^2-9(t+h)-4\right)-\left(-10t^2-9t-4\right)}{h}\]

    We cannot simply replace \(h\) with \(0\), because we cannot divide by \(0\). Instead we will simplify.

    Distribute away the outer parentheses.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-10(t+h)^2-9(t+h)-4+10t^2+9t+4}{h}\]

    Expand the squared sum. (Remember FOIL.)

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-10(t^2+2th+h^2)-9(t+h)-4+10t^2+9t+4}{h}\]

    Distribute.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-10t^2-20th-10h^2-9t-9h-4+10t^2+9t+4}{h}\]

    Combine like terms in numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-20th-10h^2-9h}{h}\]

    All the terms in the numerator have a shared factor (\(h\)). Factor out \(h\) from the numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{(-20t-10h-9)\cdot h}{h}\]

    Eliminate common factor from numerator and denominator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\left(-20t-10h-9\right)\]

    Now, since there is no possibility of dividing by \(0\), we can substitute \(0\) for \(h\).

    \[v(t)~=~-20t-10\cdot 0-9\]

    Simplify.

    \[v(t)~=~-20t-9\]

    So, \(a=-20\) and \(v_0=-9\).



  5. Question

  6. Question

    A train’s position \(x(t)\) as a function of time \(t\) can be modeled with a cubic function. \[x(t) = -5t^3-10t^2-2t-7\]

    The velocity \(v(t)\) is also a function of time. The velocity function is the derivative (with respect to time) of the position function. The derivative can be defined using a limit.

    \[v(t) ~=~ \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{x(t+h)-x(t)}{h}\]

    Using this definition (and simplifying), you will find that \(v(t)\) is a quadratic function in time.

    \[v(t) ~=~ pt^2+qt+r\]

    Determine \(p\) and \(q\) and \(r\).

    • \(p=\)
    • \(q=\)
    • \(r=\)

    The acceleration is the derivative of velocity.

    \[a(t) = \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{v(t+h)-v(t)}{h}\]

    Using this definition (and simplifying), you will find that \(a(t)\) is a linear function in time.

    \[a(t)~=~jt+a_0\]

    where \(j\) is the jerk and \(a_0\) is the initial acceleration.

    Determine \(j\) and \(a_0\).

    • \(j=\)
    • \(a_0=\)


    Solution

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(-5(t+h)^3-10(t+h)^2-2(t+h)-7\right)-\left(-5t^3-10t^2-2t-7\right)}{h}\]

    We cannot simply replace \(h\) with \(0\), because we cannot divide by \(0\). Instead we will simplify.

    Distribute away the outer parentheses.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-5(t+h)^3-10(t+h)^2-2(t+h)-7+5t^3+10t^2+2t+7}{h}\]

    Apply the rules of binomial expansion.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-5(t^3+3t^2h+3th^2+h^3)-10(t^2+2th+h^2)-2(t+h)-7+5t^3+10t^2+2t+7}{h}\]

    Distribute.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-5t^3-15t^2h-15th^2-5h^3-10t^2-20th-10h^2-2t-2h-7+5t^3+10t^2+2t+7}{h}\]

    Combine like terms in numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-15t^2h-15th^2-5h^3-20th-10h^2-2h}{h}\]

    All the terms in the numerator have a shared factor (\(h\)). Factor out \(h\) from the numerator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(-15t^2-15th-5h^2-20t-10h-2\right)\cdot h}{h}\]

    Eliminate common factor from numerator and denominator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\left(-15t^2-15th-5h^2-20t-10h-2\right)\]

    Now, since there is no possibility of dividing by \(0\), we can substitute \(0\) for \(h\).

    \[v(t)~=~-15t^2-15t\cdot 0-5\cdot 0^2-20t-10\cdot 0-2\]

    Simplify.

    \[v(t)~=~-15t^2-20t-2\]

    So, \(p=-15\) and \(q=-20\) and \(r=-2\).

    Acceleration function

    \[a(t) = \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{v(t+h)-v(t)}{h}\]

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(-15(t+h)^2-20(t+h)-2\right)-\left(-15t^2-20t-2\right)}{h}\]

    Distribute away the outer parentheses.

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-15(t+h)^2-20(t+h)-2+15t^2+20t+2}{h}\]

    Expand the squared sum. (Remember FOIL.)

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-15(t^2+2th+h^2)-20(t+h)-2+15t^2+20t+2}{h}\]

    Distribute.

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-15t^2-30th-15h^2-20t-20h-2+15t^2+20t+2}{h}\]

    Combine like terms in numerator.

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{-30th-15h^2-20h}{h}\]

    All the terms in the numerator have a shared factor (\(h\)). Factor out \(h\) from the numerator.

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{(-30t-15h-20)\cdot h}{h}\]

    Eliminate common factor from numerator and denominator.

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\left(-30t-15h-20\right)\]

    Now, since there is no possibility of dividing by \(0\), we can substitute \(0\) for \(h\).

    \[a(t)~=~-30t-15\cdot 0-20\]

    Simplify.

    \[a(t)~=~-30t-20\]

    So, \(j=-30\) and \(a_0=-20\).

  8. Question

    A train’s position \(x(t)\) as a function of time \(t\) can be modeled with a cubic function. \[x(t) = 2t^3-7t^2+5t+8\]

    • \(a_0=\)


    Solution

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{2(t+h)^3-7(t+h)^2+5(t+h)+8-2t^3+7t^2-5t-8}{h}\]

    Apply the rules of binomial expansion.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{2(t^3+3t^2h+3th^2+h^3)-7(t^2+2th+h^2)+5(t+h)+8-2t^3+7t^2-5t-8}{h}\]

    Distribute.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{2t^3+6t^2h+6th^2+2h^3-7t^2-14th-7h^2+5t+5h+8-2t^3+7t^2-5t-8}{h}\]

    Eliminate common factor from numerator and denominator.

    \[v(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\left(6t^2+6th+2h^2-14t-7h+5\right)\]

    Now, since there is no possibility of dividing by \(0\), we can substitute \(0\) for \(h\).

    \[v(t)~=~6t^2+6t\cdot 0+2\cdot 0^2-14t-7\cdot 0+5\]

    Simplify.

    \[v(t)~=~6t^2-14t+5\]

    So, \(p=6\) and \(q=-14\) and \(r=5\).

    Acceleration function

    \[a(t) = \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{v(t+h)-v(t)}{h}\]

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(6(t+h)^2-14(t+h)+5\right)-\left(6t^2-14t+5\right)}{h}\]

    Expand the squared sum. (Remember FOIL.)

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{6(t^2+2th+h^2)-14(t+h)+5-6t^2+14t-5}{h}\]

    Distribute.

    \[a(t)~=~\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{6t^2+12th+6h^2-14t-14h+5-6t^2+14t-5}{h}\]

    Combine like terms in numerator.

  16. Question

    First, we can prove that if \(f(t) = m(t)+n(t)\) then \(f'(t) = m'(t)+n'(t)\). In other words, the derivative of a sum equals the sum of the derivatives. Or, in other words, differentiation is linear. The proof follows.

    \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{f(t+h)-f(t)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(m(t+h)+n(t+h)\right)-\left(m(t)+n(t)\right)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(m(t+h)-m(t)\right)+\left(n(t+h)-n(t)\right)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\left(\frac{m(t+h)-m(t)}{h}+\frac{n(t+h)-n(t)}{h}\right)\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{m(t+h)-m(t)}{h}+\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{n(t+h)-n(t)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = m'(t)+n'(t)\]

    Also, if \(g(t) = at^b\) then \(g'(t) = (ab)t^{b-1}\). In other words, the derivative of a power function is found by multiplying the coefficient by the power and then reducing the power by one.

    Let \(f(t)\) be a function defined below: \[f(t)~=~7.2t^{9.1}+4.1t^{2.5}\]

    Using the rules above, find \(f'(0.44)\). The tolerance is \(\pm 0.01\).


    Solution

    Don’t use the definition of a derivative. We get to use the shortcuts now.

    \[f'(t) = (7.2\cdot 9.1)t^{9.1-1}+(4.1\cdot 2.5)t^{2.5-1}\]

    Simplify.

    \[f'(t) = (65.52)t^{8.1}+(10.25)t^{1.5}\]

    Now, use the given value of \(t\).

    \[f'(0.44) = (65.52)(0.44)^{8.1}+(10.25)(0.44)^{1.5}\]

    Plug the expression into a calculator.

    \[(65.52)(0.44)^{8.1}+(10.25)(0.44)^{1.5} = 3.0763848\]

    So,

    \[f'(0.44)~=~3.0763848\]


    Above, the black curve is \(y=f(t)\) and the blue (tangent) line is \(y=f'(0.44)\cdot(t-0.44)+f(0.44)\), written in point-slope form. The two intersect at point \((0.44,f(0.44))\). The slope of the tangent line equals \(f'(0.44)\), which equals 3.0763848.

  18. Question

    First, we can prove that if \(f(t) = m(t)+n(t)\) then \(f'(t) = m'(t)+n'(t)\). In other words, the derivative of a sum equals the sum of the derivatives. Or, in other words, differentiation is linear. The proof follows.

    \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{f(t+h)-f(t)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(m(t+h)+n(t+h)\right)-\left(m(t)+n(t)\right)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{\left(m(t+h)-m(t)\right)+\left(n(t+h)-n(t)\right)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\left(\frac{m(t+h)-m(t)}{h}+\frac{n(t+h)-n(t)}{h}\right)\] \[f'(t) = \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{m(t+h)-m(t)}{h}+\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{n(t+h)-n(t)}{h}\] \[f'(t) = m'(t)+n'(t)\]

    Also, if \(g(t) = at^b\) then \(g'(t) = (ab)t^{b-1}\). In other words, the derivative of a power function is found by multiplying the coefficient by the power and then reducing the power by one.

    Let \(f(t)\) be a function defined below: \[f(t)~=~8.9t^{4.3}+2t^{7.5}\]

    Using the rules above, find \(f'(0.5)\). The tolerance is \(\pm 0.01\).


    Solution

    Don’t use the definition of a derivative. We get to use the shortcuts now.

    \[f'(t) = (8.9\cdot 4.3)t^{4.3-1}+(2\cdot 7.5)t^{7.5-1}\]

    Simplify.

    \[f'(t) = (38.27)t^{3.3}+(15)t^{6.5}\]

    Now, use the given value of \(t\).

    \[f'(0.5) = (38.27)(0.5)^{3.3}+(15)(0.5)^{6.5}\]

    Plug the expression into a calculator.

    \[(38.27)(0.5)^{3.3}+(15)(0.5)^{6.5} = 4.0513406\]

    So,

    \[f'(0.5)~=~4.0513406\]


    Above, the black curve is \(y=f(t)\) and the blue (tangent) line is \(y=f'(0.5)\cdot(t-0.5)+f(0.5)\), written in point-slope form. The two intersect at point \((0.5,f(0.5))\). The slope of the tangent line equals \(f'(0.5)\), which equals 4.0513406.

  21. Question

    Consider the polynomial function below. \[f(x)=-8x^{5}+10x^{4}\]

    Determine \[f''(-0.24)\]. The tolerance is \(\pm0.01\).


    Solution

    Use the differentiation rules. Specifically the power rule along with the sum and constant multiple rules.

    \[f(x)=-8x^{5}+10x^{4}\] \[f'(x)=-40x^{4}+40x^{3}\] \[f''(x)=-160x^{3}+120x^{2}\]

    Plug in \(x=-0.24\).

    \[f''(-0.24) ~=~ -160\cdot(-0.24)^{3}+120\cdot(-0.24)^{2}\] \[f''(-0.24) ~\approx~ 9.12\]

  26. Question

    A bucket initially holds 8.1 liters of water. A hole is punched into the bottom of the bucket, so water leaks out following Torricelli’s law. Below, volume is shown as a function of time, where \(t\) in in minutes.

    \[V(t)~=~1t^2-5.7t+8.1\]

    How fast (in liters per minute) is water leaving the bucket at \(t=2.23\) minutes? (Tolerance is \(\pm 0.01\) liters per minute.) The volume in the bucket is decreasing, so the derivative will be negative, but the question is asking about the rate of water leaving, so your answer should be positive.


    Solution

    We were given the volume as a function of time.

    \[V(t) ~=~ 1t^2-5.7t+8.1\]

    Find the derivative of the volume function (with respect to time). Use the differentiation rules.

    \[V'(t) ~=~ (1\cdot 2)t^{2-1}+(-5.7\cdot 1)t^{1-1}\]

    \[V'(t) ~=~ 2t-5.7\]

    Plug the specified time \(t=2.23\) into the function.

    \[V'(2.23) ~=~ -1.24\]

    So, when \(t=2.23\), water is leaving at a rate of 1.24 liters per minute.

  31. Question

    A human converts chemical energy (energy stored as ATP and carbohydrates) into gravitational potential energy by pedaling a bicycle up a hill. During a short burst, the amount of work (stored as potential energy), as a function of time, follows the polynomial expression below, where energy (\(E\)) is in joules and time (\(t\)) is in seconds. \[E(t) ~=~ 1.79t^4-48.18t^3+364.61t^2+44.69t\]


    For your reference, 4184 joules is 1 kilocalorie (and in the US, in regards to food, we call 1 kilocalorie a “calorie”… just to be as confused as possible).

    Power is the rate of energy per time. In this case, we will measure power in watts, where 1 watt equals 1 joule per second. A human burns 100 watts as basal metabolism. Walking burns an additional 30 watts. A professional cyclist can maintain 400 watts of output while racing (see Human Power). A typical college-aged student can output 1000 watts for a few seconds. Usain Bolt’s record sprint required a burst of 2500 watts (about 3.5 horsepower) for part of the sprint. Throughout history, a laborer would average about 100 watts above basal metabolism (see Vaclav Smil).

    Anyway, at \(t=5.5\) seconds, what is the power output of the human in watts? The tolerance is \(\pm 1\) watt.


    Solution

    Find the derivative.

    \[E'(t) ~=~ 7.16t^3-144.54t^2+729.22t+44.69\]

    Plug in \(t=5.5\) seconds.

    \[E'(5.5) ~=~ 874.31\]


    So, the answer is 874 J/s or 874 watts.

  36. Question

    The graph of \(y=f(x)\) is shown below. Also, at \(x=3\), a tangent line is drawn.


    The tangent line can be used to determine the instantaneous rate of change of \(f(x)\) at \(x=3\).

    Please estimate \(f'(3)\) within the nearest hundredth. This could also be notated as \(\left.\frac{df(x)}{dx}\right|_{x=3}\) or as \(\frac{df}{dx}(3)\). For more, see wikipedia’s article on notation for differentiation.


    Solution

    Notice the tangent line intersects \(f(x)\) at point \((3,1)\). From there, follow the red line until you get to another point with integer coordinates.


    The slope of the tangent line is found with “rise over run”.

    \[m ~=~ \frac{3}{4}\]

    \[m ~=~ 0.75\]

    So, the equation of the tangent line in point-slope form is \(y=0.75(x-(3))+(1)\). More importantly for this question, the slope of the tangent line equals the instantaneous rate of change of the function, which equals the derivative at \(x=3\). In other words, \[f'(3) ~=~ 0.75\]

    \[\left.\frac{df(x)}{dx}\right|_{x=3} ~=~ 0.75\]

    \[\frac{df}{dx}(3) ~=~ 0.75\]

    Notice the tangent line intersects \(f(x)\) at point \((-2,-2)\). From there, follow the red line until you get to another point with integer coordinates.


    The slope of the tangent line is found with “rise over run”.

    \[m ~=~ \frac{1}{3}\]

    \[m ~=~ 0.3333333\]

    So, the equation of the tangent line in point-slope form is \(y=0.333(x-(-2))+(-2)\). More importantly for this question, the slope of the tangent line equals the instantaneous rate of change of the function, which equals the derivative at \(x=-2\). In other words, \[f'(-2) ~=~ 0.3333333\]

    \[\left.\frac{df(x)}{dx}\right|_{x=-2} ~=~ 0.3333333\]

    \[\frac{df}{dx}(-2) ~=~ 0.3333333\]

  41. Question

    In Calculus you will prove various differentiation rules. We already “proved” the power rule. From here on, we will just practice using the rules (and not first prove them).

    The rule to find the derivative of an exponential function is shown below, where \(a\) is a constant, and \(\ln(a)\) is the natural logarithm of \(a\).

    \[f(x) ~=~ a^x\]

    \[f'(x) ~=~ a^x\cdot\ln(a)\]

    Let \(g(x)=1.41^x\). Calculate \(g'(2.28)\). The tolerance is \(\pm 0.01\).


    Solution

    We were given \(g(x)=1.41^x\). We were told the rule to find the derivative of an exponential function.

    \[g'(x) = 1.41^x \cdot \ln(1.41)\]

    Plug in \(x=2.28\).

    \[g'(2.28) = 1.41^{2.28} \cdot \ln(1.41)\]

    \[g'(2.28) = 0.7520725\]

  46. Question

    A new business plans to produce and sells widgets.

    The long-run cost to produce each widget is dependent on the scale (size) of the operation. See economies of scale. The business models the total cost of the business with a polynomial, where \(n\) is the number of widgets made and sold. \[C(n) ~=~ 0.000015n^3+4.1n+52000\]


    The revenue from selling each widget is relatively constant until the scale of the operation is large enough to flood the market. The business models the revenue with another polynomial.

    \[R(n) ~=~ 1900n-0.000016n^3\]


    By subtracting cost from revenue, we get a profit function.

    \[P(n) ~=~ R(n)-C(n)\]

    \[P(n) ~=~ -0.000031n^3+1895.9n-52000\]

    How many widgets should the business plan to make and sell in order to maximize profit? You can solve this by finding the special number, \(n^\star\), such that \(P'(n^\star)=0\).

    The tolerance is \(\pm 10\) widgets.


    Solution

    This is called an optimization problem, where we hope to find a maximum. Since the profit function is a differentiable function, we can simply find where the derivative equals 0.

    Take a derivative of the profit function.

    \[P(n) ~=~ -0.000031n^3+1895.9n-52000\]

    \[P'(n) ~=~ -0.000093n^2+1895.9\]

    Find \(n^\star\) such that \(P'(n^\star)=0.\)

    \[-0.000093(n^\star)^2+1895.9=0\] \[-0.000093\cdot (n^\star)^2 = -1895.9\] \[(n^\star)^2 = \frac{1895.9}{0.000093}\] \[n^\star = \sqrt{\frac{1895.9}{0.000093}}\]

    \[n^\star=4515.0882057\]

  51. Question

    A designer plans to manufacture open-top cylinders by using 27.3 grams of aluminum for each cylinder. The base uses 0.05 grams per square centimeter. The sides use 0.02 grams per square centimeter. The goal is to produce a cylinder that holds as much volume as possible. How tall, in centimeters, should the cylinder be?

    The tolerance is \(\pm 0.1\) cm.


    Solution

    The total mass of the cylinder depends on the radius and height. The areal density of the bottom is multiplied by the area of the bottom to get the mass of the bottom, and the areal density of the sides are multiplied by the area of the sides to get the mass of the sides; the two masses are added to get a total mass.

    \[27.3 ~=~ 0.05\cdot\pi r^2+0.02\cdot 2\pi r h\]

    The volume the cylinder holds also depends on the radius and height.

    \[V(r,h) ~=~ \pi r^2h\]

    Solve the first equation (the mass-balance equation) for \(h\).

    \[h ~=~ \frac{27.3-0.05\cdot\pi r^2}{0.02\cdot 2\pi r}\]

    Substitute into the volume equation to express volume as a function of radius.

    \[V(r) ~=~ \pi r^2\frac{27.3-0.05\cdot\pi r^2}{0.02\cdot 2\pi r}\]

    Simplify.

    \[V(r) ~=~ \frac{27.3r}{0.04} - \frac{0.05\cdot\pi r^3}{0.04}\]

    \[V(r) ~=~ 682.5r - 1.25\pi r^3\]

    We have expressed the objective function in terms of a single variable, the radius. Now, we can differentiate \(V(r)\) with respect to \(r\).

    \[V'(r) ~=~ 682.5 - 3.75\pi r^2\]

    At the maximum, the derivative will equal 0. Let \(R\) equal the special radius that maximizes the volume.

    \[0 ~=~ 682.5 - 3.75\pi R^2\]

    \[3.75\pi R^2 ~=~ 682.5\]

    \[R^2 ~=~ \frac{682.5}{3.75\pi}\]

    \[R ~=~ \pm\sqrt{\frac{682.5}{3.75\pi}}\]

    We are only interested in the positive value.

    \[R ~=~ 7.6113336\]

    Let \(H\) be the special height that maximizes volume.

    \[H ~=~ \frac{27.3-0.05\cdot\pi (7.6113336)^2}{0.02\cdot 2\pi (7.6113336)}\]

    \[H ~=~ 19.028334\]

    We have expressed the objective function in terms of a single variable, the radius. Now, we can differentiate \(V(r)\) with respect to \(r\).

    \[V'(r) ~=~ 250 - 1.8\pi r^2\]

    At the maximum, the derivative will equal 0. Let \(R\) equal the special radius that maximizes the volume.

    \[0 ~=~ 250 - 1.8\pi R^2\]

    \[1.8\pi R^2 ~=~ 250\]

    \[R^2 ~=~ \frac{250}{1.8\pi}\]

    \[R ~=~ \pm\sqrt{\frac{250}{1.8\pi}}\]

    We are only interested in the positive value.

    \[R ~=~ 6.649038\]

    Let \(H\) be the special height that maximizes volume.

    \[H ~=~ \frac{25-0.06\cdot\pi (6.649038)^2}{0.05\cdot 2\pi (6.649038)}\]

    \[H ~=~ 7.9788456\]



  56. Question

    Which graph shows a correct pair of \(f(x)\) as a blue curve and \(f'(x)\) as a red curve? Remember the output (\(y\)) of the red derivative function should match the instantaneous slope of the blue curve for all values of \(x\).



    1. A
    2. B
    3. C
    4. D

    Solution

    The correct answer is B. Notice that when blue has positive slope, red has positive \(y\). When blue has negative slop, red has negative \(y\).

    Probably the easiest characteristic to check first is where blue has a peak or valley (so slope equals 0), the red curve should have an \(x\) intercept.

  61. Question

    The product rule tells us that if \(f(x)=g(x)\cdot h(x)\), then

    \[f'(x)~=~g'(x)\cdot h(x) ~+~ g(x)\cdot h'(x)\]

    Let’s practice using the product rule along with the power rule and the exponential rule.

    Let function \(f\) be defined below. \[f(x)~=~x^{2.9}\cdot 2.7^x\]

    Evaluate \(f'(4.5)\). The tolerance is \(\pm 1\).


    Solution

    The product rule tells us that if \(f(x)=g(x)\cdot h(x)\), then \(f'(x)~=~g'(x)\cdot h(x) ~+~ g(x)\cdot h'(x)\).

    Let \[g(x)=x^{2.9}\] and \[h(x)=2.7^x\]

    Find the derivative of each. Function \(g\) is a power function. \[g'(x)~=~ 2.9 x^{1.9}\]

    Function \(h\) is an exponential function.

    \[h'(x)~=~ 2.7^x \cdot \ln(2.7)\]

    Use those four equations in the product rule.

    \[f'(x)~=~2.9 x^{1.9}\cdot 2.7^x ~+~ x^{2.9}\cdot 2.7^x \cdot \ln(2.7)\]

    Plug in \(x=4.5\).

    \[f'(4.5)~~=~~2.9(4.5)^{1.9} 2.7^{4.5} ~~+~~ 4.5^{2.9} 2.7^{4.5} \ln(2.7)\]

    \[f'(4.5)~=~ 11212.0899847\]

  66. Question

    The area of a rectangle is the product of its width and height. A rectangle is growing both horizontally and vertically, so that both width and height are functions of time.

    \[A(t) ~=~ w(t)\cdot h(t)\]

    At \(t=3\) seconds, the width is 5.96 meters, and the height is 8.52 meters.

    \[w(3)=5.96\] \[h(3)=8.52\]

    Over a small interval of time (\(\Delta t = 0.01\) seconds) the rectangle’s width grows by \(\Delta w=0.04\) meters and the height grows by \(\Delta h =0.07\) meters, so \(w(3.01)=6\) and \(h(3.01)=8.59\). This is depicted below (not drawn to scale).


    By calculating various values, we will explore the fact that if \(\Delta w\) and \(\Delta h\) are quite small compared to \(w\) and \(h\), then the area \(\Delta w\cdot \Delta h\) is so small that we can ignore it for many purposes. In the process, we will “prove” the product rule.

    Find the area of the rectangle at \(t=3\).

    • \(A(3)=\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)

    Find the other areas in the diagram.

    • \(h(3) \Delta w=\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(w(3) \Delta h=\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(\Delta w \Delta h=\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)

    How much did the area grow by?

    • \(\Delta A ~=~ A(3.01)-A(3) ~=~\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)

    What would be the estimated growth of area if we ignored the smallest area?

    • \(h(3)\Delta w + w(3)\Delta h=\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)

    Find the final area of the rectangle.

    • \(A(3.01)=\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)

    What would be the estimated final area of the rectangle if you ignored the smallest area?

    • \(A(3)+h(3)\Delta w + w(3)\Delta h=\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)

    How fast (on average) are the width and height growing between \(t=3\) and \(t=3.01\)?

    • \(\frac{\Delta w}{\Delta t} =\) \(\mathrm{\frac{m}{s}}\)
    • \(\frac{\Delta h}{\Delta t} =\) \(\mathrm{\frac{m}{s}}\)

    What is the average rate of growth of the rectangle’s area between \(t=3\) and \(t=3.01\)?

    • \(\frac{\Delta A}{\Delta t}=\) \(\mathrm{\frac{m^2}{s}}\)

    What would be the estimated rate of growth if we ignored the smallest area?

    • \(h\cdot \frac{\Delta w}{\Delta t}~+~w\cdot \frac{\Delta h}{\Delta t}=\) \(\mathrm{\frac{m^2}{s}}\)


    Solution

    • \(A(3)=\) 50.7792 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(h(3) \Delta w=\) 0.3408 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(w(3) \Delta h=\) 0.4172 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(\Delta w \Delta h=\) 0.0028 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(\Delta A =\) 0.7608 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(h(3)\Delta w + w(3)\Delta h=\) 0.758 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(A(3.01)=\) 51.54 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(A(3)+h(3)\Delta w + w(3)\Delta h=\) 51.5372 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(\frac{\Delta w}{\Delta t} =\) 4 \(\mathrm{\frac{m}{s}}\)
    • \(\frac{\Delta h}{\Delta t} =\) 7 \(\mathrm{\frac{m}{s}}\)
    • \(\frac{\Delta A}{\Delta t}=\) 76.08 \(\mathrm{\frac{m^2}{s}}\)
    • \(h\cdot \frac{\Delta w}{\Delta t}~+~w\cdot \frac{\Delta h}{\Delta t}=\) 75.8 \(\mathrm{\frac{m^2}{s}}\)

    Notice, this suggests that in the limit as \(\Delta t \to 0\), then we get the product rule:

    \[A'(t) ~=~ w'(t)h(t)+w(t)h'(t)\]

  70. Question

    The area of a rectangle is the product of its width and height. A rectangle is growing both horizontally and vertically, so that both width and height are functions of time.

    \[A(t) ~=~ w(t)\cdot h(t)\]

    At \(t=8\) seconds, the width is 6.61 meters, and the height is 8.37 meters.

    \[w(8)=6.61\] \[h(8)=8.37\]

    Over a small interval of time (\(\Delta t = 0.01\) seconds) the rectangle’s width grows by \(\Delta w=0.11\) meters and the height grows by \(\Delta h =0.04\) meters, so \(w(8.01)=6.72\) and \(h(8.01)=8.41\). This is depicted below (not drawn to scale).


    By calculating various values, we will explore the fact that if \(\Delta w\) and \(\Delta h\) are quite small compared to \(w\) and \(h\), then the area \(\Delta w\cdot \Delta h\) is so small that we can ignore it for many purposes. In the process, we will “prove” the product rule.

    Find the area of the rectangle at \(t=8\).

    • \(A(8)=\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)

    Find the other areas in the diagram.

    • \(h(8) \Delta w=\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(w(8) \Delta h=\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(\Delta w \Delta h=\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)

    How much did the area grow by?

    • \(\Delta A ~=~ A(8.01)-A(8) ~=~\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)

    What would be the estimated growth of area if we ignored the smallest area?

    • \(h(8)\Delta w + w(8)\Delta h=\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)

    Find the final area of the rectangle.

    • \(A(8.01)=\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)

    What would be the estimated final area of the rectangle if you ignored the smallest area?

    • \(A(8)+h(8)\Delta w + w(8)\Delta h=\) \(\mathrm{m^2}\)

    How fast (on average) are the width and height growing between \(t=8\) and \(t=8.01\)?

    • \(\frac{\Delta w}{\Delta t} =\) \(\mathrm{\frac{m}{s}}\)
    • \(\frac{\Delta h}{\Delta t} =\) \(\mathrm{\frac{m}{s}}\)

    What is the average rate of growth of the rectangle’s area between \(t=8\) and \(t=8.01\)?

    • \(\frac{\Delta A}{\Delta t}=\) \(\mathrm{\frac{m^2}{s}}\)

    What would be the estimated rate of growth if we ignored the smallest area?

    • \(h\cdot \frac{\Delta w}{\Delta t}~+~w\cdot \frac{\Delta h}{\Delta t}=\) \(\mathrm{\frac{m^2}{s}}\)


    Solution

    • \(A(8)=\) 55.3257 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(h(8) \Delta w=\) 0.9207 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(w(8) \Delta h=\) 0.2644 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(\Delta w \Delta h=\) 0.0044 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(\Delta A =\) 1.1895 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(h(8)\Delta w + w(8)\Delta h=\) 1.1851 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(A(8.01)=\) 56.5152 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(A(8)+h(8)\Delta w + w(8)\Delta h=\) 56.5108 \(\mathrm{m^2}\)
    • \(\frac{\Delta w}{\Delta t} =\) 11 \(\mathrm{\frac{m}{s}}\)
    • \(\frac{\Delta h}{\Delta t} =\) 4 \(\mathrm{\frac{m}{s}}\)
    • \(\frac{\Delta A}{\Delta t}=\) 118.95 \(\mathrm{\frac{m^2}{s}}\)
    • \(h\cdot \frac{\Delta w}{\Delta t}~+~w\cdot \frac{\Delta h}{\Delta t}=\) 118.51 \(\mathrm{\frac{m^2}{s}}\)

    Notice, this suggests that in the limit as \(\Delta t \to 0\), then we get the product rule:

    \[A'(t) ~=~ w'(t)h(t)+w(t)h'(t)\]



  71. Question

    Let \(f(x)=x^3-6x^2-28x-30\). A tangent line is drawn through \((-2, -6)\). Find the equation of the tangent line in slope-intercept form (\(y=mx+b\)).

    • \(m=\)
    • \(b=\)


    Solution

    We were given \(f(x)=x^3-6x^2-28x-30\). Differentiate to find the derivative.

    \[f'(x)=3x^2-12x-28\]

    Find the instantaneous rate of change at \(x=-2\).

    \[f'(-2) = 8\] The derivative of \(f(x)\) at \(x=-2\) equals the slope of the tangent line. \[m=8\]

    At this stage there are two good options. We either substitute into \(y=mx+b\) with \(y=-6\), \(m=8\), and \(x=-2\) to find \(b\) or simplify the point-slope (\(y=m(x-x_0)+y_0\)) form into slope-intercept form.

    Option 1: plug point \((-2, -6)\) into \(y=8x+b\) to get \(b\)

    We already know the slope. \[y=8x+b\] We know the line must go through point \((-2, -6)\). \[-6=(8)(-2)+b\]

    \[-6=-16+b\]

    \[10=b\]

    So the tangent line is expressed with the equation \(y=8x+10\)

    Option 2: simplify point-slope form

    We already know a point (-2,-6) and the slope, \(m=8\), of the line. Plug into \(y=m(x-x_0)+y_0\).

    \[y=8(x+2)-6\]

    Distribute. \[y=8x+16-6\] Combine the constants. \[y=8x+10\]

    Answer

    \[m=8\] \[b=-12\]

    So, the equation of the tangent line is known:

    \[y=8x+10\]



  72. Question

    Let \(f(x)=x^3+6x^2+8x+7\). A tangent line is drawn through \((-2, 7)\). Find the equation of the tangent line in slope-intercept form (\(y=mx+b\)).

    • \(m=\)
    • \(b=\)

    Option 1: plug point \((-2, 7)\) into \(y=-4x+b\) to get \(b\)

    Answer

    So, the equation of the tangent line is known:

    \[y=-4x-1\]

  76. Question

    A chef is deciding how much salt to add to a dish. They’ve determined that utility (\(u\) in “utils”) is a function of the mass of salt (\(x\) in grams).

    \[u(x) = 2x^{6}-6x^{10}\]

    What is the optimal mass of salt to maximize utility? (You can assume only positive amounts of salt are possible. The tolerance is \(\pm0.01\) grams.)


    Solution

    We were given \(u(x) = 2x^{6}-6x^{10}\). Differentiate to find derivative function.

    \[u'(x) = 12x^{5}-60x^{9}\]

    Set the derivative function equal to 0 to find extrema.

    \[12x^{5}-60x^{9} = 0\] Factor out \(x^{5}\).

    \[(12-60x^{4})x^{5} = 0\]

    We are not interested in when \(x=0\). So, we can just consider the other factor. \[12-60x^{4} = 0\] \[12=60x^{4}\] \[\frac{12}{60}=x^{4}\] \[\sqrt[4]{\frac{12}{60}}=x\]

    So…

    \[x=\left(\frac{12}{60}\right)^{1/4}\]

    \[x = 0.6687403\]
